<TITLE> UK house price inflation accelerates in June-govt </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Aug 13 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British house price inflation picked up to its highest in over two years in June, suggesting rising interest rates and affordability constraints have yet to strangle demand. House prices in Britain rose 12.1 percent year-on-year in June -- its highest since March 2005 -- compared with a revised 10.8 percent increase in May, government data showed on Monday. The rise took the average house price to 214,222 pounds. The rise was led by London where annual house price inflation picked up to 17.5 percent from 14.3 percent in May. "There is no denying that the house price data are markedly stronger than expected and suggest that the housing market is proving resilient to higher interest rates," said Howard Archer at Global Insight. Reports from mortgage lenders also suggest house price inflation has remained robust in the face of rising interest rates although most lenders expect the market to slow later this year. The figures from the Department for Communities and Local Government are based on sale completions and thus lag other surveys. However, they are considered the most accurate gauge of house price inflati
